    <h2>Why this work matters</h2>
    <p>Hawk's 1949 dissertation is the most thorough single-author treatment of Oregon's Common School Fund — what the Oregon Constitution and the 1859 Admissions Act called the "irreducible" fund. The work covers federal and state land policy, federal and state administration of the lands, the development of the irreducible school fund itself, and the fund's condition as of the late 1940s.</p>

    <p>The project's Oregon substrate cites Hawk repeatedly. Where the encyclopedia's Oregon entry needs to anchor a claim about pre-1950 Oregon school-fund administration to a single secondary source, Hawk is usually the source.</p>

    <h2>About the digitization and OCR</h2>
    <p>The PDF held by this library is a 2018 digitization of the original 1949 typewritten thesis. The scan is high-resolution but the typewriter face, paper aging, and photocopy generation make OCR brittle. A <code>.txt</code> companion exists in the project's primary-source archive and can be searched with care, but quoted passages should always be verified against the PDF image rather than the OCR text.</p>

    <p>For users who want to work with Hawk extensively, the recommended path is to download the PDF and read the relevant chapter directly from the scan. We are not, at this stage, attempting a full markdown extraction.</p>

    <h2>Read the full text</h2>
    <p>The full PDF is hosted in this library's primary-source archive: <a href="/sources/hawk_09072018_final.pdf"><strong>Download Hawk (PDF, 89 MB)</strong></a>. The file is large — give it a moment to load.</p>

